{"title_page": "Marko Maruli\u0107", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Marko Maruli\u0107\n| image = Marco Marulo 1903 Ljetopis dru\u0161tva hrvatskih knji\u017eevnika za 1900-1903.jpg\n| alt =\n| caption = 1903 illustration\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_date = 18 August 1450\n| birth_place = [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Republic of Venice]]\n| death_date = {{death date|df=yes|1524|1|5}} (aged 73)\n| death_place = [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Republic of Venice]]\n| occupation = [[poet]], [[humanism|humanist]]\n| language    = [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Latin language|Latin]] \n| period      = [[Renaissance]]\n| genre = \n| movement =\n| notableworks = ''[[Judita]]''<br /> ''[[Davidiad]]''\n}}\n'''Marko Maruli\u0107 Spli\u0107anin''' ({{IPA-sh|m\u00e2\u02d0rko m\u01cerulit\u0255|hr}}),{{efn|Marko Maruli\u0107 Spli\u0107anin is the form he himself used to sign his works. It means Marko Maruli\u0107 of Split.}} in Latin '''Marcus Marulus Spalatensis'''{{efn|Alternative Latin forms include Marcus de Marulis and Marcus Marulus Dalmata (\"the Dalmatian\").}} and Italian '''Marco Marulo''' (18 August 1450 \u2013 5 January 1524), was a [[Croatian language|Croatian]] poet and [[Renaissance humanism|Renaissance humanist]]. He coined the term \"[[psychology]]\".<ref>Darko Zubrinic, Zagreb (1995) [http://www.croatianhistory.net/etf/lat.html#maru Croatian Humanists, Ecumenists, Latinists, and Encyclopaedists]. croatianhistory.net</ref><ref name=\"HJP\">{{cite web|url=http://hjp.novi-liber.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=dl1nUBI|title=psihologija|work=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|language=Croatian|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4SS0fcbm3xMC&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25|title=The Sciences of the Soul: The Early Modern Origins of Psychology|last=Vidal|first=Fernando|year=2011|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|page=25}}</ref>\n\nHe is regarded as the Croatian [[national poet]] and has been called the \"crown of the Croatian medieval age\" and the \"father of the Croatian Renaissance\".<ref name=\"Marulianum\">[http://www.knjizevni-krug.hr/marulianum/index.asp Marulianum] ''Center for study of Marko Maruli\u0107 and his literary activity.'' \u2013 Retrieved on  28 November 2008.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMaruli\u0107 was a [[nobleman]] born in [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Dalmatia]], coming from the distinguished aristocratic family of ''Pe\u010deni\u0107'' (''Pecini\u0107'', ''Picini\u0107''), the 15th century family branch whose founder was Petar, and only began calling themselves again Maruli\u0107, ''Marulus'' or  ''De Marulis'', in the 16th century.<ref name=\"Marulianum\" />\n\nVery little is actually known about his life, and the few facts that have survived to this day are fairly unreliable. It is certain that he attended a school run by a humanist scholar ''Tideo Acciarini'' in his hometown. Having completed it, he is then speculated to have graduated law at the [[Padua University]], after which he spent much of his life in his home town. Occasionally he visited [[Venice]] (to trade) and [[Rome]] (to celebrate the year 1500).\n\nHe lived for about two years in ''Ne\u010dujam'' on the island of [[\u0160olta]]. In Split, Maruli\u0107 practised law, serving as a [[judge]], examinator of notarial entries and executor of wills. Owing to his work, he became the most distinguished person of the humanist circle in Split.\n\n==Writing==\nThe central figure of the humanist circle in Split, Maruli\u0107 was inspired by the [[Bible]], Antique writers and Christian hagiographies. Main topics of his writings were [[Christian theology|Christian theological]] by nature. He was a poet and writer who wrote many poems, discussions on theology and Christian ethics, stories and some epics.<ref name=\"Marulianum\" /> He wrote in three languages: [[Latin language|Latin]] (more than 80% of his preserved opus), [[Croatian language|Croatian]] and Vulgar [[Italian language|Italian]] (three letters and two [[sonnet]]s are preserved). Maruli\u0107 was active in the struggles against the Ottoman Turks who were invading the Croatian lands at that time. He wrote, among other works, an ''Epistola'' to the [[Pope]] where he begged for assistance in the fight against the [[Ottomans]].\n\n=== Latin works ===\n [[File:Marko Marulic Evangelistarium.jpg|thumb|170px| Cover sheet of Maruli\u0107's ''Evangelistarium'', 1571 [[Tuscan language|Tuscan]]-language edition, translated by Silvano Razzi from Latin original.]]\nHis [[Europe]]an fame rested mainly on his works written in Latin which had been published and re-published during 16th and 17th century and translated into many languages. He published ''Psichiologia de ratione animae humanae'' containing the earliest known literary reference to [[psychology]]. He wrote ''De institutione bene vivendi per exempla sanctorum'', a moralist tractate of Biblical inspiration which he managed to publish in 1506 in [[Venice]]; this work influenced [[St Francis Xavier]], and it was claimed by one of Francis' associates in 1549 to be the only book that he read during his missionary work. Maruli\u0107 also wrote the ''Evanglistarium'', a systematic discourse on ethical principles that he managed to publish in 1516, and in 1517 the ''[[Davidiad]]'' a religious epic which fused Biblical motifs and antique, Virgilian poetics in 14 books, the most important being the story on the life of the Biblical [[King David]]. Unfortunately, the ''Davidiad'' was discovered only in 1924, only to be lost again and rediscovered finally in 1952. However, Maruli\u0107's Latin works of devotional and religious provenance, once adored and envied across Europe, shared the destiny that befell the Humanist genre of those centuries: they vanished into oblivion.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010212024749/http://www.moderna-vremena.hr/vrem/marul.asp Moderna Vremena i Marko Maruli\u0107]  \u2013 Retrieved on  28 November 2008.</ref>\n\n=== Croatian works ===\n[[File:Spomenik Marku Maruli\u0107u u Kninu.JPG|thumb|Monument in [[Knin]]]]\n[[File:Marko Marulic bust.jpg|thumb|right|Bust of Marko Maruli\u0107 by [[Ivan Me\u0161trovi\u0107]] in [[Split, Croatia|Split]].]]\nIn the works written in Croatian, Maruli\u0107 achieved a permanent status and position that has remained uncontested. His central Croatian oeuvre, the epic [[poem]] ''[[Judita]]'' (''{{lang|hr|Libar Marca Marula Splichianina V chomse sdarsi Istoria Sfete udouice Iudit u uersih haruacchi slosena chacho ona ubi uoiuodu Olopherna Posridu uoische gnegoue i oslodobi puch israelschi od ueliche pogibili}}'') written in 1501 and published in Venice in 1521, is based on the Biblical tale from a Deuterocanonical [[Book of Judith]], written in [[\u010cakavian dialect]] \u2013 his [[mother tongue]] and described by him as ''u versi haruacchi slozhena'' (\"arranged in Croatian stanzas\"). His other works in Croatian are:\n\n* ''Suzana'' (Susan) \u2013 biblical poem in 780 stanzas, listing Croatian works at the end and theming Babylon Jewish woman falsely accused on adultery\n* ''Poklad i korizma'' (Carnival and Lent), ''Spovid koludric od sedam smrtnih grihov'' (Nun's confession of seven deadly sins), ''Anka satir'' (Anka the satire) \u2013 secular [[poetry]], poems dedicated to his sister ''Bira''\n* ''Tu\u017eenje grada Hjerosolima'' (Jerusalem's Lament) \u2013 anti-Turkish laments\n* ''Molitva suprotiva Turkom'' (Prayer against the Turks) \u2013 poem in 172 doubly rhymed [[dodecasyllable|dodecasyllablic]] stanzas of anti-Turkish theme, written between 1493 and 1500. Poem has a hidden [[acrostic]] ''Solus deus potes nos liberare de tribulatione inimicorum nostrorum Turcorum sua potentia infinita'', \"Only God with his infinite might can save us from the misery of our enemies Turks\", discovered by [[Luko Paljetak]]. The poem is assumed to exhibit influence of [[Juraj \u0160i\u017egori\u0107]]'s  ''Elegija o pusto\u0161enju \u0160ibenskog polja'' and medieval song ''Spasi, Marije, tvojih vjernih'' from [[Tkonski miscellany]]. This Maruli\u0107's work influenced [[Petar Zorani\u0107|Zorani\u0107]]'s ''[[Planine]]'' \u2013 the first Croatian novel, in which ''ganka pastira Marula'' is sung alluding to Turks, and also to [[Petar Lu\u010di\u0107]] and his work ''Molitva Bogu protiv Turkom'', and [[Primo\u017e Trubar]]'s ''Pjesni zuper Turke''.<ref>[http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/ndd/08kolovoz/0818%20Marulic.html Marko Maruli\u0107] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215121617/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/ndd/08kolovoz/0818%20Marulic.html |date=15 February 2009 }} ''at HRT archives.'' \u2013 Retrieved on 28 November 2008.</ref>\n\nAmerican historian [[John Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.]] emphasizes that Maruli\u0107 belongs to a group of humanist and clerics placed in the \"Croat\" camp who, at least at the time when they wrote their texts, did not seem to have \"Croat\" identity, particularly not a Croat ethnic identity.<ref name=\"Jr.2006\">{{cite book|last=Jr.|first=John V. A. Fine|title=When Ethnicity Did Not Matter in the Balkans: A Study of Identity in Pre-Nationalist Croatia, Dalmatia, and Slavonia in the Medieval and Early-Modern Periods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wEF5oN5erE0C&pg=PA273|date=1 January 2006|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=0-472-02560-0|page=273|quote= Thus it seems that identity as \"Croat\", and particularly one with a feeling for such as an ethnic identity, was missing - at least at the time when those men wrote their texts - in all these figures. And they I might add included two figures placed in the \"Croat\" camp at the beginning of the chapter: Marko Maruli\u0107 and \u0160imun Ko\u017ei\u0107}}</ref>\n\n=== Glasgow codex ===\n\nRecently discovered manuscript of Marko Maruli\u0107 in the University Library, [[Glasgow]] throws a new light on his work and persona. It was discovered in 1995 by Darko Novakovi\u0107 and he states that in comparison with Maruli\u0107's known carmina minora the poems in the codex introduce three thematic novelties. Unexpectedly vehement, satirical epigrams are featured and the intensity of his satirical impulse is startling: even in such conventional poems as epitaphs. Three poems reveal his love of animals. The greatest revelation are the verses which show Maruli\u0107 as the author of love poems. This aspect represents the most serious challenge to our traditional picture of the Poet: the last epigram in the collection is a true Priapeum marked with lascivious ambiguity.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://hrcak.srce.hr/9568|title=Dva nepoznata Maruli\u0107eva rukopisa u Velikoj Britaniji: MS. ADD. A. 25 u oxfordskoj Bodleiani i Hunter 334 u Sveu\u010dili\u0161noj knji\u017enici u Glasgowu|journal=Colloquia Maruliana|volume=6|date=April 1997|format=PDF|language=hr|accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Illustrated page from the second edition of Judita by Marko Maruli\u0107, 1522.jpg|thumb|Marko Maruli\u0107's illustration for Judita, a page from second edition, Zadar 1522.]]\n[[File:Order of DH Marko Maruli\u0107.jpg|thumb|[[Order of Danica Hrvatska]] with face of Marko Maruli\u0107 is Croatian state decoration awarded for special merits for culture]]\n\n==Visual artist==\n\nAccording to Fiskovi\u0107,<ref>C. Fiskovi\u0107: O Maruli\u0107evu slikanju, Prilozi povijesti umjetnosti u Dalmaciji,\nSplit 1986-87, str. 393-424.</ref> Maruli\u0107 was an accomplished illustrator. In his will he leaves to his sister a book that he illustrated and conceived.<ref>http://www.magicus.info/hr/magicus/tekst.php?id=14245</ref> The second edition of ''Judita'', prepared by Zadar publisher Jerolim Mirkovi\u0107, dated 30 May 1522 is adorned with nine woodcuts of which the last one is signed \"M\". It is assumed that the illustrations were created by Maruli\u0107 himself.<ref>http://db.nsk.hr/HeritageDetails.aspx?id=873</ref>\n\n== Currency and medals ==\n\nMaruli\u0107's portrait is depicted on the [[Obverse and reverse|obverse]] of the Croatian 500 [[Croatian kuna|kuna]] banknote, issued in 1993.<ref>[http://www.hnb.hr Croatian National Bank]. [http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/enovcan.htm?tsfsg=5caabbb4dca58151e125c650d3cdae36 Features of Kuna Banknotes]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506012028/http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/enovcan.htm?tsfsg=5caabbb4dca58151e125c650d3cdae36 |date=6 May 2009 }}: [http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/novcanice/e500k.htm?tsfsg=a649438eb16231e47533d70f5e0ed4c4 500 kuna] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604014206/http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/novcanice/e500k.htm?tsfsg=a649438eb16231e47533d70f5e0ed4c4 |date=4 June 2011 }}. \u2013 Retrieved on 30 March 2009.</ref>\n\nCroatian state decoration awarded for special merits for culture, [[Order of Danica Hrvatska]] is ornamented with the face of Marko Maruli\u0107.<ref>File:Order of DH Marko Maruli\u0107.jpg</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category}} {{Wikisourcelang|hr|Marko Maruli\u0107}}\n* {{citation|title=Encyclopedia of Christian Civilization (s. v. \u2018Marulus, Marcus\u2019)| first1=Franz|last1=Posset | first2=G.T.|last2=Kurian |year=2011 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|location=Oxford }}\n* {{citation| title=The Maruli\u0107 Reader|author1=Bratislav Lu\u010din  |year=2008|publisher=Knji\u017eevni krug Split| location=Split}}\n* {{citation| title=Marko Maruli\u0107 Marulus: An Outstanding Contribution to European Humanism; in Croatia and Europe II \u2013 Croatia in the late Middle Ages and the Renaissance: A Cultural Survey |author1=Mirko Tomasovi\u0107 |year=2008|publisher=\u0160kolska knjiga \u2013 Philip Wilson Publishers| location=London and Zagreb}}\n* {{citation| title=Zbornik radova o Marku Maruli\u0107u; u povodu 550. obljetnice ro\u0111enja i 500. obljetnice njegove Judite 1450.-1501.-2001 = Collected Papers on Marko Maruli\u0107. In celebration of 550th anniversary of his birth and 500th anniversary of the birth of his Judita 1450-1501-2001|author1=Dubravko Jel\u010di\u0107 |year=2005|publisher=HAZU| location=Zagreb|language=Croatian, English}}\n* {{citation| title=Marcus Marulus and the Biblia Latina of 1489. An approach to his biblical hermeneutics|author1=Franz Posset |year=2013|publisher=B\u00f6hlau | location=Cologne}}\n* {{citation|title=Leksikon hrvatskih pisaca| first1=Dunja |last1=Fali\u0161evac | first2=Kre\u0161imir |last2=Nemec | first3=Darko |last3=Novakovi\u0107 |year=2000 |publisher=\u0160kolska knjiga d.d|location=Zagreb | isbn=953-0-61107-2 |language=Croatian}}\n* {{citation| title=Marko Maruli\u0107 Marul : monografija |author1=Mirko Tomasovi\u0107 |year=1999 |publisher=Erasmus naklada \u2013 Knji\u017eevni krug Split, Marulianum \u2013 Zavod za znanost o knji\u017eevnosti Filozofskog fakulteta u Zagrebu| location=Zagreb-Split|language=Croatian, English, French, German, Italian}}\n* {{citation| title=Zbornik u proslavu petstogodi\u0161njice ro\u0111enja Marka Maruli\u0107a 1450\u20131950|author1=Josip Badali\u0107|author2=Nikola Majnari\u0107|year=1950 |publisher=HAZU| location=Zagreb|language=Croatian}}\n* {{citation| title=Hrvatska knji\u017eevnost u europskom kontekstu|author1=Ivan Slamnig|authorlink=Ivan Slamnig|year=1978 |publisher=SN Liber| location=Zagreb|language=Croatian}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home Marcus Marulus Spalatensis (site of the Marulianum, Centre for Studies on Marko Maruli\u0107 and his Humanist Circle]\n* [http://www.liberius.net/livre.php?id_livre=692 ''Vita Marci Maruli Spalatensis per Franciscum Natalem, conciuem suum, composita''] (Latin text and French translation)\n* [http://www.croatianhistory.net/etf/lat.html#maru Marko Maruli\u0107, the \"father of Croatian literature\"]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home/old-editions Links to digitized old editions of Maruli\u0107's books]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home/links-to-works-about-marulic Links to works about Maruli\u0107 in English, German, Italian, and Spanish] \n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home/translations-on-internet Links to translations of Maruli\u0107's works in English, French, German, Icelandic, Italian, Portuguese, and Spanish]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080607005812/http://marulianum.storia.unipd.it/lang/en/ Project VALMAR: Valorizzazione e recupero degli scritti e dei luoghi dell'umanista spalatino Marko Maruli\u0107/Marcus Marulus]\n* [http://hrcak.srce.hr/colloquia-maruliana?lang=en \"Colloquia Maruliana\" on Hr\u010dak, portal of scientific journals of Croatia]\n* [http://www.liberius.net/auteur.php?id_auth=303 French translations of several works of Maruli\u0107]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081029210639/http://www.bulaja.com/marulic/djela/judita/str1.htm Facsimile of the ''editio princeps'' of ''Judita'', Venice, 1521]\n* {{Find a Grave|7696972}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081029210639/http://www.bulaja.com/marulic/djela/judita/str1.htm Facsimile of the ''editio princeps'' of ''Judita'', Venice, 1521]\n* [http://dk.nsk.hr/stara_knjiga/NSK_SK_ID03/ Zadar edition of Judita with illustrations by Marko Maruli\u0107]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marulic, Marko}}\n[[Category:1450 births]]\n[[Category:1524 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Split, Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian Renaissance humanists]]\n[[Category:Christian humanists]]\n[[Category:16th-century Croatian poets]]\n[[Category:Catholic poets]]\n[[Category:16th-century Latin-language writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Croatian people]]\n[[Category:15th-century Croatian people]]\n[[Category:New Latin-language poets]]\n[[Category:Republic of Venice poets]]\n[[Category:Venetian Slavs]]\n[[Category:Venetian period in the history of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian male poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Marko Maruli\u0107\n| image = Marco Marulo 1903 Ljetopis dru\u0161tva hrvatskih knji\u017eevnika za 1900-1903.jpg\n| alt =\n| caption = 1903 illustration\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_date = 18 August 1450\n| birth_place = [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Republic of Venice]]\n| death_date = {{death date|df=yes|1524|1|5}} (aged 73)\n| death_place = [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Republic of Venice]]\n| occupation = [[poet]], [[humanism|humanist]]\n| language    = [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Latin language|Latin]] \n| period      = [[Renaissance]]\n| genre = \n| movement =\n| notableworks = ''[[Judita]]''<br /> ''[[Davidiad]]''\n}}\n'''Marko Maruli\u0107 Spli\u0107anin''' ({{IPA-sh|m\u00e2\u02d0rko m\u01cerulit\u0255|hr}}),{{efn|Marko Maruli\u0107 Spli\u0107anin is the form he himself used to sign his works. It means Marko Maruli\u0107 of Split.}} in Latin '''Marcus Marulus Spalatensis'''{{efn|Alternative Latin forms include Marcus de Marulis and Marcus Marulus Dalmata (\"the Dalmatian\").}} and Italian '''Marco Marulo''' (18 August 1450 \u2013 5 January 1524), was a [[Croatian language|Croatian]] poet and [[Renaissance humanism|Renaissance humanist]]. He coined the term \"[[psychology]]\".<ref>Darko Zubrinic, Zagreb (1995) [http://www.croatianhistory.net/etf/lat.html#maru Croatian Humanists, Ecumenists, Latinists, and Encyclopaedists]. croatianhistory.net</ref><ref name=\"HJP\">{{cite web|url=http://hjp.novi-liber.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=dl1nUBI|title=psihologija|work=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|language=Croatian|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4SS0fcbm3xMC&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25|title=The Sciences of the Soul: The Early Modern Origins of Psychology|last=Vidal|first=Fernando|year=2011|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|page=25}}</ref>\n\nHe is regarded as the Croatian [[national poet]] and has been called the \"crown of the Croatian medieval age\" and the \"father of the Croatian Renaissance\".<ref name=\"Marulianum\">[http://www.knjizevni-krug.hr/marulianum/index.asp Marulianum] ''Center for study of Marko Maruli\u0107 and his literary activity.'' \u2013 Retrieved on  28 November 2008.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMaruli\u0107 was a [[nobleman]] born in [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Dalmatia]], coming from the distinguished aristocratic family of ''Pe\u010deni\u0107'' (''Pecini\u0107'', ''Picini\u0107''), the 15th century family branch whose founder was Petar, and only began calling themselves again Maruli\u0107, ''Marulus'' or  ''De Marulis'', in the 16th century.<ref name=\"Marulianum\" />\n\nVery little is actually known about his life, and the few facts that have survived to this day are fairly unreliable. It is certain that he attended a school run by a humanist scholar ''Tideo Acciarini'' in his hometown. Having completed it, he is then speculated to have graduated law at the [[Padua University]], after which he spent much of his life in his home town. Occasionally he visited [[Venice]] (to trade) and [[Rome]] (to celebrate the year 1500).\n\nHe lived for about two years in ''Ne\u010dujam'' on the island of [[\u0160olta]]. In Split, Maruli\u0107 practised law, serving as a [[judge]], examinator of notarial entries and executor of wills. Owing to his work, he became the most distinguished person of the humanist circle in Split.\n\n==Writing==\nThe central figure of the humanist circle in Split, Maruli\u0107 was inspired by the [[Bible]], Antique writers and Christian hagiographies. Main topics of his writings were [[Christian theology|Christian theological]] by nature. He was a poet and writer who wrote many poems, discussions on theology and Christian ethics, stories and some epics.<ref name=\"Marulianum\" /> He wrote in three languages: [[Latin language|Latin]] (more than 80% of his preserved opus), [[Croatian language|Croatian]] and Vulgar [[Italian language|Italian]] (three letters and two [[sonnet]]s are preserved). Maruli\u0107 was active in the struggles against the Ottoman Turks who were invading the Croatian lands at that time. He wrote, among other works, an ''Epistola'' to the [[Pope]] where he begged for assistance in the fight against the [[Ottomans]].\n\n=== Latin works ===\n [[File:Marko Marulic Evangelistarium.jpg|thumb|170px| Cover sheet of Maruli\u0107's ''Evangelistarium'', 1571 [[Tuscan language|Tuscan]]-language edition, translated by Silvano Razzi from Latin original.]]\nHis [[Europe]]an fame rested mainly on his works written in Latin which had been published and re-published during 16th and 17th century and translated into many languages. He published ''Psichiologia de ratione animae humanae'' containing the earliest known literary reference to [[psychology]]. He wrote ''De institutione bene vivendi per exempla sanctorum'', a moralist tractate of Biblical inspiration which he managed to publish in 1506 in [[Venice]]; this work influenced [[St Francis Xavier]], and it was claimed by one of Francis' associates in 1549 to be the only book that he read during his missionary work. Maruli\u0107 also wrote the ''Evanglistarium'', a systematic discourse on ethical principles that he managed to publish in 1516, and in 1517 the ''[[Davidiad]]'' a religious epic which fused Biblical motifs and antique, Virgilian poetics in 14 books, the most important being the story on the life of the Bilbical [[King David]]. Unfortunately, the ''Davidiad'' was discovered only in 1924, only to be lost again and rediscovered finally in 1952. However, Maruli\u0107's Latin works of devotional and religious provenance, once adored and envied across Europe, shared the destiny that befell the Humanist genre of those centuries: they vanished into oblivion.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010212024749/http://www.moderna-vremena.hr/vrem/marul.asp Moderna Vremena i Marko Maruli\u0107]  \u2013 Retrieved on  28 November 2008.</ref>\n\n=== Croatian works ===\n[[File:Spomenik Marku Maruli\u0107u u Kninu.JPG|thumb|Monument in [[Knin]]]]\n[[File:Marko Marulic bust.jpg|thumb|right|Bust of Marko Maruli\u0107 by [[Ivan Me\u0161trovi\u0107]] in [[Split, Croatia|Split]].]]\nIn the works written in Croatian, Maruli\u0107 achieved a permanent status and position that has remained uncontested. His central Croatian oeuvre, the epic [[poem]] ''[[Judita]]'' (''{{lang|hr|Libar Marca Marula Splichianina V chomse sdarsi Istoria Sfete udouice Iudit u uersih haruacchi slosena chacho ona ubi uoiuodu Olopherna Posridu uoische gnegoue i oslodobi puch israelschi od ueliche pogibili}}'') written in 1501 and published in Venice in 1521, is based on the Biblical tale from a Deuterocanonical [[Book of Judith]], written in [[\u010cakavian dialect]] \u2013 his [[mother tongue]] and described by him as ''u versi haruacchi slozhena'' (\"arranged in Croatian stanzas\"). His other works in Croatian are:\n\n* ''Suzana'' (Susan) \u2013 biblical poem in 780 stanzas, listing Croatian works at the end and theming Babylon Jewish woman falsely accused on adultery\n* ''Poklad i korizma'' (Carnival and Lent), ''Spovid koludric od sedam smrtnih grihov'' (Nun's confession of seven deadly sins), ''Anka satir'' (Anka the satire) \u2013 secular [[poetry]], poems dedicated to his sister ''Bira''\n* ''Tu\u017eenje grada Hjerosolima'' (Jerusalem's Lament) \u2013 anti-Turkish laments\n* ''Molitva suprotiva Turkom'' (Prayer against the Turks) \u2013 poem in 172 doubly rhymed [[dodecasyllable|dodecasyllablic]] stanzas of anti-Turkish theme, written between 1493 and 1500. Poem has a hidden [[acrostic]] ''Solus deus potes nos liberare de tribulatione inimicorum nostrorum Turcorum sua potentia infinita'', \"Only God with his infinite might can save us from the misery of our enemies Turks\", discovered by [[Luko Paljetak]]. The poem is assumed to exhibit influence of [[Juraj \u0160i\u017egori\u0107]]'s  ''Elegija o pusto\u0161enju \u0160ibenskog polja'' and medieval song ''Spasi, Marije, tvojih vjernih'' from [[Tkonski miscellany]]. This Maruli\u0107's work influenced [[Petar Zorani\u0107|Zorani\u0107]]'s ''[[Planine]]'' \u2013 the first Croatian novel, in which ''ganka pastira Marula'' is sung alluding to Turks, and also to [[Petar Lu\u010di\u0107]] and his work ''Molitva Bogu protiv Turkom'', and [[Primo\u017e Trubar]]'s ''Pjesni zuper Turke''.<ref>[http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/ndd/08kolovoz/0818%20Marulic.html Marko Maruli\u0107] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215121617/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/ndd/08kolovoz/0818%20Marulic.html |date=15 February 2009 }} ''at HRT archives.'' \u2013 Retrieved on 28 November 2008.</ref>\n\nAmerican historian [[John Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.]] emphasizes that Maruli\u0107 belongs to a group of humanist and clerics placed in the \"Croat\" camp who, at least at the time when they wrote their texts, did not seem to have \"Croat\" identity, particularly not a Croat ethnic identity.<ref name=\"Jr.2006\">{{cite book|last=Jr.|first=John V. A. Fine|title=When Ethnicity Did Not Matter in the Balkans: A Study of Identity in Pre-Nationalist Croatia, Dalmatia, and Slavonia in the Medieval and Early-Modern Periods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wEF5oN5erE0C&pg=PA273|date=1 January 2006|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=0-472-02560-0|page=273|quote= Thus it seems that identity as \"Croat\", and particularly one with a feeling for such as an ethnic identity, was missing - at least at the time when those men wrote their texts - in all these figures. And they I might add included two figures placed in the \"Croat\" camp at the beginning of the chapter: Marko Maruli\u0107 and \u0160imun Ko\u017ei\u0107}}</ref>\n\n=== Glasgow codex ===\n\nRecently discovered manuscript of Marko Maruli\u0107 in the University Library, [[Glasgow]] throws a new light on his work and persona. It was discovered in 1995 by Darko Novakovi\u0107 and he states that in comparison with Maruli\u0107's known carmina minora the poems in the codex introduce three thematic novelties. Unexpectedly vehement, satirical epigrams are featured and the intensity of his satirical impulse is startling: even in such conventional poems as epitaphs. Three poems reveal his love of animals. The greatest revelation are the verses which show Maruli\u0107 as the author of love poems. This aspect represents the most serious challenge to our traditional picture of the Poet: the last epigram in the collection is a true Priapeum marked with lascivious ambiguity.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://hrcak.srce.hr/9568|title=Dva nepoznata Maruli\u0107eva rukopisa u Velikoj Britaniji: MS. ADD. A. 25 u oxfordskoj Bodleiani i Hunter 334 u Sveu\u010dili\u0161noj knji\u017enici u Glasgowu|journal=Colloquia Maruliana|volume=6|date=April 1997|format=PDF|language=hr|accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Illustrated page from the second edition of Judita by Marko Maruli\u0107, 1522.jpg|thumb|Marko Maruli\u0107's illustration for Judita, a page from second edition, Zadar 1522.]]\n[[File:Order of DH Marko Maruli\u0107.jpg|thumb|[[Order of Danica Hrvatska]] with face of Marko Maruli\u0107 is Croatian state decoration awarded for special merits for culture]]\n\n==Visual artist==\n\nAccording to Fiskovi\u0107,<ref>C. Fiskovi\u0107: O Maruli\u0107evu slikanju, Prilozi povijesti umjetnosti u Dalmaciji,\nSplit 1986-87, str. 393-424.</ref> Maruli\u0107 was an accomplished illustrator. In his will he leaves to his sister a book that he illustrated and conceived.<ref>http://www.magicus.info/hr/magicus/tekst.php?id=14245</ref> The second edition of ''Judita'', prepared by Zadar publisher Jerolim Mirkovi\u0107, dated 30 May 1522 is adorned with nine woodcuts of which the last one is signed \"M\". It is assumed that the illustrations were created by Maruli\u0107 himself.<ref>http://db.nsk.hr/HeritageDetails.aspx?id=873</ref>\n\n== Currency and medals ==\n\nMaruli\u0107's portrait is depicted on the [[Obverse and reverse|obverse]] of the Croatian 500 [[Croatian kuna|kuna]] banknote, issued in 1993.<ref>[http://www.hnb.hr Croatian National Bank]. [http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/enovcan.htm?tsfsg=5caabbb4dca58151e125c650d3cdae36 Features of Kuna Banknotes]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506012028/http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/enovcan.htm?tsfsg=5caabbb4dca58151e125c650d3cdae36 |date=6 May 2009 }}: [http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/novcanice/e500k.htm?tsfsg=a649438eb16231e47533d70f5e0ed4c4 500 kuna] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604014206/http://www.hnb.hr/novcan/novcanice/e500k.htm?tsfsg=a649438eb16231e47533d70f5e0ed4c4 |date=4 June 2011 }}. \u2013 Retrieved on 30 March 2009.</ref>\n\nCroatian state decoration awarded for special merits for culture, [[Order of Danica Hrvatska]] is ornamented with the face of Marko Maruli\u0107.<ref>File:Order of DH Marko Maruli\u0107.jpg</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category}} {{Wikisourcelang|hr|Marko Maruli\u0107}}\n* {{citation|title=Encyclopedia of Christian Civilization (s. v. \u2018Marulus, Marcus\u2019)| first1=Franz|last1=Posset | first2=G.T.|last2=Kurian |year=2011 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|location=Oxford }}\n* {{citation| title=The Maruli\u0107 Reader|author1=Bratislav Lu\u010din  |year=2008|publisher=Knji\u017eevni krug Split| location=Split}}\n* {{citation| title=Marko Maruli\u0107 Marulus: An Outstanding Contribution to European Humanism; in Croatia and Europe II \u2013 Croatia in the late Middle Ages and the Renaissance: A Cultural Survey |author1=Mirko Tomasovi\u0107 |year=2008|publisher=\u0160kolska knjiga \u2013 Philip Wilson Publishers| location=London and Zagreb}}\n* {{citation| title=Zbornik radova o Marku Maruli\u0107u; u povodu 550. obljetnice ro\u0111enja i 500. obljetnice njegove Judite 1450.-1501.-2001 = Collected Papers on Marko Maruli\u0107. In celebration of 550th anniversary of his birth and 500th anniversary of the birth of his Judita 1450-1501-2001|author1=Dubravko Jel\u010di\u0107 |year=2005|publisher=HAZU| location=Zagreb|language=Croatian, English}}\n* {{citation| title=Marcus Marulus and the Biblia Latina of 1489. An approach to his biblical hermeneutics|author1=Franz Posset |year=2013|publisher=B\u00f6hlau | location=Cologne}}\n* {{citation|title=Leksikon hrvatskih pisaca| first1=Dunja |last1=Fali\u0161evac | first2=Kre\u0161imir |last2=Nemec | first3=Darko |last3=Novakovi\u0107 |year=2000 |publisher=\u0160kolska knjiga d.d|location=Zagreb | isbn=953-0-61107-2 |language=Croatian}}\n* {{citation| title=Marko Maruli\u0107 Marul : monografija |author1=Mirko Tomasovi\u0107 |year=1999 |publisher=Erasmus naklada \u2013 Knji\u017eevni krug Split, Marulianum \u2013 Zavod za znanost o knji\u017eevnosti Filozofskog fakulteta u Zagrebu| location=Zagreb-Split|language=Croatian, English, French, German, Italian}}\n* {{citation| title=Zbornik u proslavu petstogodi\u0161njice ro\u0111enja Marka Maruli\u0107a 1450\u20131950|author1=Josip Badali\u0107|author2=Nikola Majnari\u0107|year=1950 |publisher=HAZU| location=Zagreb|language=Croatian}}\n* {{citation| title=Hrvatska knji\u017eevnost u europskom kontekstu|author1=Ivan Slamnig|authorlink=Ivan Slamnig|year=1978 |publisher=SN Liber| location=Zagreb|language=Croatian}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home Marcus Marulus Spalatensis (site of the Marulianum, Centre for Studies on Marko Maruli\u0107 and his Humanist Circle]\n* [http://www.liberius.net/livre.php?id_livre=692 ''Vita Marci Maruli Spalatensis per Franciscum Natalem, conciuem suum, composita''] (Latin text and French translation)\n* [http://www.croatianhistory.net/etf/lat.html#maru Marko Maruli\u0107, the \"father of Croatian literature\"]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home/old-editions Links to digitized old editions of Maruli\u0107's books]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home/links-to-works-about-marulic Links to works about Maruli\u0107 in English, German, Italian, and Spanish] \n* [https://sites.google.com/site/marcusmarulusen/home/translations-on-internet Links to translations of Maruli\u0107's works in English, French, German, Icelandic, Italian, Portuguese, and Spanish]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080607005812/http://marulianum.storia.unipd.it/lang/en/ Project VALMAR: Valorizzazione e recupero degli scritti e dei luoghi dell'umanista spalatino Marko Maruli\u0107/Marcus Marulus]\n* [http://hrcak.srce.hr/colloquia-maruliana?lang=en \"Colloquia Maruliana\" on Hr\u010dak, portal of scientific journals of Croatia]\n* [http://www.liberius.net/auteur.php?id_auth=303 French translations of several works of Maruli\u0107]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081029210639/http://www.bulaja.com/marulic/djela/judita/str1.htm Facsimile of the ''editio princeps'' of ''Judita'', Venice, 1521]\n* {{Find a Grave|7696972}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081029210639/http://www.bulaja.com/marulic/djela/judita/str1.htm Facsimile of the ''editio princeps'' of ''Judita'', Venice, 1521]\n* [http://dk.nsk.hr/stara_knjiga/NSK_SK_ID03/ Zadar edition of Judita with illustrations by Marko Maruli\u0107]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marulic, Marko}}\n[[Category:1450 births]]\n[[Category:1524 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Split, Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian Renaissance humanists]]\n[[Category:Christian humanists]]\n[[Category:16th-century Croatian poets]]\n[[Category:Catholic poets]]\n[[Category:16th-century Latin-language writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Croatian people]]\n[[Category:15th-century Croatian people]]\n[[Category:New Latin-language poets]]\n[[Category:Republic of Venice poets]]\n[[Category:Venetian Slavs]]\n[[Category:Venetian period in the history of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian male poets]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marko_Maruli%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Cindy Williams", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Cindy Williams\n| image       = Cindy Williams.JPG\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     =  Williams in ''Laverne & Shirley''\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1947|8|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Van Nuys]], Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Bill Hudson (singer)|Bill Hudson]] <br>|1982|2000|end=divorced}}\n| children    = 2\n| years_active = 1970\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actress\n}}\n\n'''Cynthia Jane Williams''' (born August 22, 1947) is an American actress known for her role as Shirley Feeney on the television sitcom ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' (1976\u20131982).\n\n==Early life==\nWilliams was born in [[Van Nuys]], Los Angeles, California to Francesca (n\u00e9e Bellini) and Beachard Williams,  an electronic technician.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> The family moved to Dallas, Texas when she was a year old and returned to the [[San Fernando Valley]] when she was 10.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" >{{cite web|title=CINDY WILLIAMS|url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/cindy-williams#|website=Archive of American Television|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref> She has one sibling, a sister, Carol Ann. Her maternal grandparents immigrated to America from Mineo, a municipality in the Province of Catania, rendering Williams of Sicilian descent.\n\nWilliams wrote<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> and acted, during childhood, at a Church and later acted<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> at [[Birmingham High School]], graduating in 1965.  She attended Los Angeles City College with a theater major.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /><!-- graduated?? -->\n\n==Career==\nAfter college, Williams began her professional career by landing national commercials, which included [[Foster Grant]] sunglasses and [[TWA]].<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> Her first roles in television, among others, were on ''[[Room 222]]'',<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> ''[[Nanny and the Professor]]'' and ''[[Love, American Style]]''.\n\nWilliams accompanied an actor-friend from Los Angeles City College who needed a scene partner for the audition and was also accepted at [[The Actors Studio West]], but rarely attended due to acting commitments<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superiorpics.com/cindy_williams/|title=The Cindy Williams Picture Pages|publisher=SuperiorPics.som |date= |accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |quote=|first=David |last=Garfield |title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|url=https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf/page/278 278]|chapter=Appendix: Life Members of The Actors Studio as of January 1980}}</ref> Williams picked up important film roles early in her career: [[George Cukor]]'s ''[[Travels with My Aunt (film)|Travels with My Aunt]]'' (1972); as Laurie Henderson, [[Ron Howard]]'s character's high school sweetheart in [[George Lucas]]'s ''[[American Graffiti]]'' (1973) for which she earned a [[BAFTA]] nomination as Best Supporting Actress;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/1975/film/supporting-actress|title=BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org}}</ref> and [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s ''[[The Conversation]]'' (1974). She auditioned for Lucas's next project, ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'', but lost the role of [[Princess Leia]] to [[Carrie Fisher]].<ref>{{cite news |title=George Lucas and the Trials and Tribulations of a Trilogy: 'Empire of Dreams'|first=Frazier |last=Moore |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jLkiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OrUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3259,2894232&dq=cindy-williams+princess-leia+auditioned&hl=en |newspaper=The Beaver County Times |date=2004-09-10 |accessdate=2012-12-09 }}</ref>\n\nWilliams met Penny Marshall, first on a double date, later, at [[Francis Ford Coppola]]\u2019s Zoetrope company,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2012/04/27/its-the-tv-land-of-milk-and-honey/ |work = Saint Paul Pioneer Press |title=It\u2019s the TV Land of milk and honey|date=2012-04-27}}</ref> both hired as comedy writers, because \"they wanted two women\",<ref name=\"Penny-Marshall\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-05-21-tv-4110-story.html|title=Retro : Reunion of the Milwaukee Madcaps : 'LAVERNE & SHIRLEY' SPECIAL LOOKS BACK AT A SITCOM THAT BROUGHT NOSTALGIA TO THE LATE 70S|date=1995-05-21|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2020-02-05}}</ref> on a prospective TV spoof for the [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial]].<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> While writing at Zoetrope, Penny\u2019s brother, Garry, called to ask if they would like to make a guest appearance on, ''Happy Days'', his TV series.\n\nIn 1975, Williams was cast as a fun-loving brewery bottle capper,<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> Shirley Feeney, in an episode of ''[[Happy Days]]'' with [[Penny Marshall]], who played her best friend and roommate [[Laverne De Fazio]]. The girls were cast as \"sure-thing\"<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /><ref name=\"Penny-Marshall\" >{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sYe2gYZ3AHcC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=Coppola+Zoetrope+Bicentennial+Williams&hl=en|title=My Mother was Nuts: A Memoir|first=Penny|last=Marshall|date=2012-02-05|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|accessdate=2020-02-05|via=Google Books}}</ref> dates of [[Richie Cunningham|Richie]] and [[Fonzie]] ([[Henry Winkler]]), and their appearance proved so popular that [[Garry Marshall]], producer of ''Happy Days'' and Penny Marshall's brother, commissioned a spin-off for the characters. Williams continued her role on the very successful ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' from 1976 until 1982. Although praised for her portrayal of Shirley, Williams left the show after the second episode of the show's eighth and final season, after she became pregnant with her first child. Williams and co-star Marshall had been feuding for quite some time, and this had also spurred her decision to leave.<ref>{{cite book|quote=|first=Marley |last=Brant|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3XnpqmYAxcC&pg=PA81 |title=Happier Days: Paramount Television's Golden Sitcoms|year=2006|publisher=Billboard Books|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-8933-9|page=81|chapter=Triumph and Tribulation}}</ref>  They would reconcile a few years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/penny-marshall-talks-cancer-abortion-reconciling-with-laverne-shirley-co-star-in-new-memoir|title=Penny Marshall talks cancer, abortion, reconciling with 'Laverne & Shirley co-star in new memoir|first=Nicki|last=Gostin|date=March 26, 2015|website=Fox News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/news/165914_laverne_shirley_star_cindy_williams_spills_show_secrets_new_tell_all|title='Laverne & Shirley' Star Cindy Williams Spills Show Secrets in New Tell-All|website=Entertainment Tonight}}</ref> The success of the Garry Marshall series led to a Saturday morning animated series ''[[Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour]]'', created by [[Hanna-Barbera]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=mork+and+mindy&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2474|title=Mork & Mindy / Laverne & Shirley and the Fonz Hour, The @ Toonarific Cartoons|website=www.toonarific.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Williams returned to series TV in the short-lived sitcom ''Normal Life'', and a couple years later, reunited with former ''Laverne & Shirley'' producers [[Thomas L. Miller]] and [[Robert L. Boyett]] to star in their family sitcom ''[[Getting By]]'' (1993\u201394). She has guest starred on several television shows, including two episodes of ''[[8 Simple Rules]]''.\n\nWilliams has performed onstage in the national tours of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]], [[Deathtrap (play)|Deathtrap]]'' and ''[[Moon Over Buffalo]]'', and a regional production of ''[[Nunsense]]''. She reunited with her ''Laverne & Shirley'' co-star [[Eddie Mekka]] in a November 2008 regional production of the [[Ren\u00e9e Taylor]]-[[Joseph Bologna]] comedy play ''It Had to Be You''.<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/122906.html \"Laverne & Shirley\" Stars Williams and Mekka to Reunite for ''It Had to Be You''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081103094052/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/122906.html |date=2008-11-03 }} from ''[[Playbill]]''</ref>\n\n[[File:Cindy Williams 2017.jpg|thumb|left|Williams in 2017]]\n\nShe made her Broadway debut as daffy Mrs. Tottendale in  ''[[The Drowsy Chaperone]]'' at the [[Marquis Theatre]] on December 11, 2007, succeeding [[JoAnne Worley]] in the role originated by [[Georgia Engel]].<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/113223.html \"Doing It Her Way: Cindy Williams to Get ''Drowsy'' Beginning Dec. 11\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207012529/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/113223.html |date=2007-12-07 }} from ''[[Playbill]]''</ref>\n\nWilliams reunited with her ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' co-star [[Penny Marshall]] on ''[[Sam & Cat]]'' in the episode \"#SalmonCat\" (2013).<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/06/26/penny-marshall-and-cindy-williams-to-reunite-on-nickelodeons-sam-cat/189259/ |title=Penny Marshall and Cindy Williams to Reunite on Nickelodeon's 'Sam & Cat' |publisher=TVbytheNumbers |date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/laverne-shirley-stars-reunite-nick-comedy-101222356.html |title='Laverne & Shirley' stars reunite on Nick comedy |publisher=Yahoo.com |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tv.yahoo.com/news/laverne-shirley-stars-penny-marshall-cindy-williams-reunite-212429625.html |title=Laverne & Shirley Stars Penny Marshall, Cindy Williams To Reunite On Nickelodeon's Sam & Cat |publisher=Yahoo!TV |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, her memoir ''Shirley, I Jest!'' (co-written with Dave Smitherman) was published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/cindy-williams-reveals-real-reason-she-left-laverne-shirley-t25226|title=Why did Cindy Williams leave Laverne with no Shirley?|website=TODAY.com}}</ref> In the same year, Williams engaged in [[celebrity branding]] for the [[senior citizen]] service [[Visiting Angels]].<ref>\"Visiting Angels Tailored in Home Care Featuring Cindy Willams.\" ''I Spot.TV''. Accessed 5 Aug. 2017. https://www.ispot.tv/ad/7Ut3/visiting-angels-tailored-in-home-care-feat-cindywillams</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams was married to [[Bill Hudson (singer)|Bill Hudson]] of the musical trio [[Hudson Brothers]] in 1982. The marriage ended in divorce in 2000. Together they have two children: a daughter, Emily (born 1982) and a son, Zachary (born 1986). Williams is a practicing Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeryl-brunner/cindy-williams-nunsense_b_1511639.html|title=With Her New Nunsense Touring Show, Cindy Williams Kicks WITH a Habit|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailytimes.com/Weekend/story/Cindy-Williams-sees-a-bit-of-Laverne--Shirley-in-Nunset-Boulevard-id-028987|title=Cindy Williams sees a bit of \u2018Laverne & Shirley\u2019 in \u2018Nunset Boulevard\u2019|work=The Daily Times}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1970: ''[[Gas-s-s-s]]'' as Marissa\n*1971: ''[[Drive, He Said]]'' as Manager's Girlfriend\n*1972: ''[[Beware! The Blob]]'' as Randy's Girl\n*1972: ''[[Travels with My Aunt (film)|Travels with My Aunt]]'' as Tooley\n*1973: ''[[American Graffiti]]'' as Laurie Henderson\n:* BAFTA nomination<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" />\n*1973: ''[[The Killing Kind (1973 film)|The Killing Kind]]'' as Lori Davis\n*1974: ''[[The Conversation]]'' as Ann\n*1975: ''[[Mr. Ricco]]'' as Jamison\n*1976: ''[[The First Nudie Musical]]'' as Rosie\n*1979: ''[[More American Graffiti]]'' as Laurie Henderson Bolander\n*1983: ''[[The Creature Wasn't Nice]]'' as Annie McHugh\n*1985: ''[[UFOria]]'' as Arlene Stewart\n*1985: ''The Joy of Natural Childbirth'' as Herself\n*1989: ''[[Big Man on Campus]]'' as Diane Girard\n*1989: ''[[Rude Awakening (film)|Rude Awakening]]'' as June Margolin\n*1991: ''[[Bingo (1991 film)|Bingo]]'' as Natalie Devlin\n*1997: ''[[Meet Wally Sparks]]'' as Emily Preston\n*2002: ''[[The Biggest Fan]]'' as Debbie's Mom\n*2006: ''The Legend of William Tell'' as Jillian\n*2012: ''Stealing Roses'' as Rose\n*2018: ''Waiting in the Wings: Still Waiting'' as Rosie\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Television===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1971: ''[[The Funny Side]]'' (6 episodes) as Teenage Wife\n*1973: ''[[Love, American Style]]'' as Karen Brown (segment \"Love and the Time Machine\") / Naomi Brubaker (segment \"Love and the Face Bow\")\n*1974: ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' (6.18 \"Secret Witness\") as Sue Reynolds\n*1974: ''The Migrants'' (TV Movie) as Betty\n*1974: ''[[Cannon]]'' (The Stalker) as June Bowers\n*1975\u20131979: ''[[Happy Days]]'' (5 episodes) as Shirley Feeney\n*1976\u20131982: ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' (159 episodes) as Shirley Feeney\n:*1978 [[Golden Globes]] nomination for Best TV Actress - Musical/Comedy<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" />\n*1978:  ''[[Suddenly, Love]]'' (TV movie) as Regina Malloy\n*1981\u20131982: ''[[Laverne & Shirley (1981 TV series)|Laverne & Shirley in the Army]]'' (13 episodes) as Shirley Feeney (voice)\n*1982: ''[[Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour]]'' (1 episode) as Shirley (voice)\n*1985: ''When Dreams Come True'' (TV Movie) as Susan Matthews\n*1986: ''Help Wanted: Kids'' as Lisa Burke\n*1986: ''The Leftovers'' as Heather Drew\n*1988: ''Save the Dog!'' (TV Movie) as Becky\n*1988: ''Tricks of the Trade'' (TV Movie) as Catherine\n*1990: ''[[Perry Mason (TV movies)|Perry Mason: The Case of the Poisoned Pen]]'' (TV Movie) as Rita Sue Bliss\n*1990: ''[[Normal Life (TV series)|Normal Life]]'' (13 episodes) as Anne Harlow\n*1990: ''Menu for Murder'' (TV Movie) as Connie Mann\n*1991: ''Earth Angel'' (TV Movie) as Judith\n*1993\u20131994: ''[[Getting By]]'' (31 episodes) as Cathy Hale\n*1994: ''[[Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'' as Wandamae\n*1995: ''[[Escape from Terror: The Teresa Stamper Story]]'' (TV Movie) as Wanda Walden\n*1995: ''The Laverne & Shirley Reunion'' as Herself\n*1995: ''[[The Magic School Bus (TV series)|The Magic School Bus]]'' (1 episode) as Gerri Poveri (voice)\n*1996: ''[[The Stepford Husbands]]'' (TV Movie) as Caroline Knox\n*1999: ''[[The Patty Duke Show#Reunion movie|The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights]]'' (TV Movie) as Sue Ellen Caldwell\n*2000\u20132001: ''[[Strip Mall]]'' (6 episodes) as Herself\n*2000\u20132002: ''[[For Your Love (TV series)|For Your Love]]'' (3 episodes) as Ronnie\n*2002: ''Laverne & Shirley Together Again'' (TV Movie) as Herself / Shirley Feeney\n*2003: ''[[8 Simple Rules]]'' as Mary Ellen Doyle\n*2004: ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as Nora Hodges\n*2007: ''[[Drive (2007 TV series)|Drive]]'' as House Mother\n*2012: ''Strawberry Summer'' (Hallmark name), ''Easy Heart'' (Pixl name) (TV Movie) as Ruth Yates\n*2013: ''[[Sam & Cat]]'' as Janice Dobbins\n*2016: ''[[The Odd Couple (2015 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'' as Vivian\n*2016: ''A Dream of Christmas'' (TV Movie) as Jayne 'The Angel'\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|930286|Cindy Williams}}\n*{{emmytvlegends name|cindy-williams}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qchV2eC9oOQ Video] Discussion with Actress Cindy Williams at [[New York Film Academy]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Cindy}}\n\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Hudson family (show business)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles City College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Van Nuys, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Cindy Williams\n| image       = Cindy Williams.JPG\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     =  Williams in ''Laverne & Shirley''\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1947|8|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Van Nuys]], Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Bill Hudson (singer)|Bill Hudson]] <br>|1982|2000|end=divorced}}\n| children    = 2\n| years_active = 1970\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actress\n}}\n\n'''Cynthia Jane Williams''' (born August 22, 1947) is an American actress known for her role as Shirley Feeney on the television sitcom ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' (1976\u20131982).\n\n==Early life==\nWilliams was born in [[Van Nuys]], Los Angeles, California to Francesca (n\u00e9e Bellini) and Beachard Williams,  an electronic technician.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> The family moved to Dallas, Texas when she was a year old and returned to the [[San Fernando Valley]] when she was 10.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" >{{cite web|title=CINDY WILLIAMS|url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/cindy-williams#|website=Archive of American Television|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref> She has one sibling, a sister, Carol Ann. Her maternal grandparents immigrated to America from Mineo, a municipality in the Province of Catania, rendering Williams of Sicilian descent.\n\nWilliams wrote<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> and acted, during childhood, at a Church and later acted<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> at [[Birmingham High School]], graduating in 1965.  She attended Los Angeles City College with a theater major.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /><!-- graduated?? -->\n\n==Career==\nAfter college, Williams began her professional career by landing national commercials, which included [[Foster Grant]] sunglasses and [[TWA]].<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> Her first roles in television, among others, were on ''[[Room 222]]'',<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> ''[[Nanny and the Professor]]'' and ''[[Love, American Style]]''.\n\nWilliams accompanied an actor-friend from Los Angeles City College who needed a scene partner for the audition and was also accepted at [[The Actors Studio West]], but rarely attended due to acting commitments<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superiorpics.com/cindy_williams/|title=The Cindy Williams Picture Pages|publisher=SuperiorPics.som |date= |accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |quote=|first=David |last=Garfield |title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|url=https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf/page/278 278]|chapter=Appendix: Life Members of The Actors Studio as of January 1980}}</ref> Williams picked up important film roles early in her career: [[George Cukor]]'s ''[[Travels with My Aunt (film)|Travels with My Aunt]]'' (1972); as Laurie Henderson, [[Ron Howard]]'s character's high school sweetheart in [[George Lucas]]'s ''[[American Graffiti]]'' (1973) for which she earned a [[BAFTA]] nomination as Best Supporting Actress;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/1975/film/supporting-actress|title=BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org}}</ref> and [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s ''[[The Conversation]]'' (1974). She auditioned for Lucas's next project, ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'', but lost the role of [[Princess Leia]] to [[Carrie Fisher]].<ref>{{cite news |title=George Lucas and the Trials and Tribulations of a Trilogy: 'Empire of Dreams'|first=Frazier |last=Moore |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jLkiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OrUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3259,2894232&dq=cindy-williams+princess-leia+auditioned&hl=en |newspaper=The Beaver County Times |date=2004-09-10 |accessdate=2012-12-09 }}</ref>\n\nWilliams met Penny Marshall, first on a double date, later, at [[Francis Ford Coppola]]\u2019s Zoetrope company,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2012/04/27/its-the-tv-land-of-milk-and-honey/ |work = Saint Paul Pioneer Press |title=It\u2019s the TV Land of milk and honey|date=2012-04-27}}</ref> both hired as comedy writers, because \"they wanted two women\",<ref name=\"Penny-Marshall\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-05-21-tv-4110-story.html|title=Retro : Reunion of the Milwaukee Madcaps : 'LAVERNE & SHIRLEY' SPECIAL LOOKS BACK AT A SITCOM THAT BROUGHT NOSTALGIA TO THE LATE 70S|date=1995-05-21|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2020-02-05}}</ref> on a prospective TV spoof for the [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial]].<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> While writing at Zoetrope, Penny\u2019s brother, Garry, called to ask if they would like to make a guest appearance on, ''Happy Days'', his TV series.\n\nIn 1975, Williams was cast as a fun-loving brewery bottle capper,<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /> Shirley Feeney, in an episode of ''[[Happy Days]]'' with [[Penny Marshall]], who played her best friend and roommate [[Laverne De Fazio]]. The girls were cast as \"sure-thing\"<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" /><ref name=\"Penny-Marshall\" >{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sYe2gYZ3AHcC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=Coppola+Zoetrope+Bicentennial+Williams&hl=en|title=My Mother was Nuts: A Memoir|first=Penny|last=Marshall|date=2012-02-05|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|accessdate=2020-02-05|via=Google Books}}</ref> dates of [[Richie Cunningham|Richie]] and [[Fonzie]] ([[Henry Winkler]]), and their appearance proved so popular that [[Garry Marshall]], producer of ''Happy Days'' and Penny Marshall's brother, commissioned a spin-off for the characters. Williams continued her role on the very successful ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' from 1976 until 1982. Although praised for her portrayal of Shirley, Williams left the show after the second episode of the show's eighth and final season, after she became pregnant with her first child. Williams and co-star Marshall had been feuding for quite some time, and this had also spurred her decision to leave.<ref>{{cite book|quote=|first=Marley |last=Brant|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3XnpqmYAxcC&pg=PA81 |title=Happier Days: Paramount Television's Golden Sitcoms|year=2006|publisher=Billboard Books|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-8933-9|page=81|chapter=Triumph and Tribulation}}</ref>  They would reconcile a few years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/penny-marshall-talks-cancer-abortion-reconciling-with-laverne-shirley-co-star-in-new-memoir|title=Penny Marshall talks cancer, abortion, reconciling with 'Laverne & Shirley co-star in new memoir|first=Nicki|last=Gostin|date=March 26, 2015|website=Fox News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/news/165914_laverne_shirley_star_cindy_williams_spills_show_secrets_new_tell_all|title='Laverne & Shirley' Star Cindy Williams Spills Show Secrets in New Tell-All|website=Entertainment Tonight}}</ref> The success of the Garry Marshall series led to a Saturday morning animated series ''[[Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour]]'', created by [[Hanna-Barbera]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=mork+and+mindy&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2474|title=Mork & Mindy / Laverne & Shirley and the Fonz Hour, The @ Toonarific Cartoons|website=www.toonarific.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Williams returned to series TV in the short-lived sitcom ''Normal Life'', and a couple years later, reunited with former ''Laverne & Shirley'' producers [[Thomas L. Miller]] and [[Robert L. Boyett]] to star in their family sitcom ''[[Getting By]]'' (1993\u201394). She has guest starred on several television shows, including two episodes of ''[[8 Simple Rules]]''.\n\nWilliams has performed onstage in the national tours of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]], [[Deathtrap (play)|Deathtrap]]'' and ''[[Moon Over Buffalo]]'', and a regional production of ''[[Nunsense]]''. She reunited with her ''Laverne & Shirley'' co-star [[Eddie Mekka]] in a November 2008 regional production of the [[Ren\u00e9e Taylor]]-[[Joseph Bologna]] comedy play ''It Had to Be You''.<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/122906.html \"Laverne & Shirley\" Stars Williams and Mekka to Reunite for ''It Had to Be You''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081103094052/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/122906.html |date=2008-11-03 }} from ''[[Playbill]]''</ref>\n\n[[File:Cindy Williams 2017.jpg|thumb|left|Williams in 2017]]\n\nShe made her Broadway debut as daffy Mrs. Tottendale in  ''[[The Drowsy Chaperone]]'' at the [[Marquis Theatre]] on December 11, 2007, succeeding [[JoAnne Worley]] in the role originated by [[Georgia Engel]].<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/113223.html \"Doing It Her Way: Cindy Williams to Get ''Drowsy'' Beginning Dec. 11\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207012529/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/113223.html |date=2007-12-07 }} from ''[[Playbill]]''</ref>\n\nWilliams reunited with her ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' co-star [[Penny Marshall]] on ''[[Sam & Cat]]'' in the episode \"#SalmonCat\" (2013).<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/06/26/penny-marshall-and-cindy-williams-to-reunite-on-nickelodeons-sam-cat/189259/ |title=Penny Marshall and Cindy Williams to Reunite on Nickelodeon's 'Sam & Cat' |publisher=TVbytheNumbers |date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/laverne-shirley-stars-reunite-nick-comedy-101222356.html |title='Laverne & Shirley' stars reunite on Nick comedy |publisher=Yahoo.com |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tv.yahoo.com/news/laverne-shirley-stars-penny-marshall-cindy-williams-reunite-212429625.html |title=Laverne & Shirley Stars Penny Marshall, Cindy Williams To Reunite On Nickelodeon's Sam & Cat |publisher=Yahoo!TV |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, her memoir ''Shirley, I Jest!'' (co-written with Dave Smitherman) was published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/cindy-williams-reveals-real-reason-she-left-laverne-shirley-t25226|title=Why did Cindy Williams leave Laverne with no Shirley?|website=TODAY.com}}</ref> In the same year, Williams engaged in [[celebrity branding]] for the [[senior citizen]] service [[Visiting Angels]].<ref>\"Visiting Angels Tailored in Home Care Featuring Cindy Willams.\" ''I Spot.TV''. Accessed 5 Aug. 2017. https://www.ispot.tv/ad/7Ut3/visiting-angels-tailored-in-home-care-feat-cindywillams</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams was married to [[Bill Hudson (singer)|Bill Hudson]] of the musical trio [[Hudson Brothers]] in 1982. The marriage ended in divorce in 2000. Together they have two children: a daughter, Emily (born 1982) and a son, Zachary (born 1986). Williams is a practicing Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeryl-brunner/cindy-williams-nunsense_b_1511639.html|title=With Her New Nunsense Touring Show, Cindy Williams Kicks WITH a Habit|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailytimes.com/Weekend/story/Cindy-Williams-sees-a-bit-of-Laverne--Shirley-in-Nunset-Boulevard-id-028987|title=Cindy Williams sees a bit of \u2018Laverne & Shirley\u2019 in \u2018Nunset Boulevard\u2019|work=The Daily Times}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1970: ''[[Gas-s-s-s]]'' as Marissa\n*1971: ''[[Drive, He Said]]'' as Manager's Girlfriend\n*1972: ''[[Beware! The Blob]]'' as Randy's Girl\n*1972: ''[[Travels with My Aunt (film)|Travels with My Aunt]]'' as Tooley\n*1973: ''[[American Graffiti]]'' as Laurie Henderson\n:* BAFTA nomination<ref name=\"emmytvlegends\" 