ge&q=lets%20switch%20penny%20marshall&f=false|title=New York Magazine|last=LLC|first=New York Media|date=April 22, 1985|publisher=New York Media, LLC|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1975 || ''Wives'' || Connie || Television film\n|-\n|1975 || ''[[Chico and the Man]]'' || Anita Cappuccino || Episode: \"Chico and the Van\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|1975 || ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' || Herself || Episode: \"Rob Reiner\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1975\u20131979 || ''[[Happy Days]]'' || Laverne DeFazio || 5 episodes<ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|-\n|1976 || ''[[Good Heavens]]'' || || Episode: \"Take Me Out to the Ball Game\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Single Season Sitcoms, 1948-1979: A Complete Guide|last=Leszczak|first=Bob|publisher=McFarland|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=59}}</ref>\n|-\n|1976\u20131983 || ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' || Laverne DeFazio || 178 episodes<ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|-\n|1977 || ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' || Herself || Episode: \"Live from Mardi Gras\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1977 || ''[[Blansky's Beauties]]'' || Laverne DeFazio || Episode: \"Nancy Remembers Laverne\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|1978 || ''[[Mork & Mindy]]'' || Laverne DeFazio || Episode: \"Pilot\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1978 || ''More Than Friends'' || Matty Perlman || Television film<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|1979 || ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]'' || Herself || Episode #1.3<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paleycenter.org/collection/item/?q=Carol+Plus+Two&p=1&item=T:46646|title=The Paley Center for Media|website=The Paley Center for Media|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|1981\u20131982 || ''[[Laverne & Shirley (1981 TV series)|Laverne & Shirley in the Army]]'' || Laverne DeFazio || Voice, 13 episodes<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://celebrity.nine.com.au/2018/12/19/06/13/penny-marshall-actress-director-dies-at-75|title=Penny Marshall, 'Laverne & Shirley' star, director, dies at 75|website=celebrity.nine.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|1982 || ''[[Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour]]'' || Laverne DeFazio || Voice, 8 episodes (''Laverne & Shirley with the Fonz'' segment)<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1983 || ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]'' || Herself || Episode: \"Louie Moves Uptown\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1984 || ''[[The New Show]]'' || Various Characters || Episode #1.4<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sctvguide.ca/episodes/as_newshow.htm|title=SCTV Guide - After SCTV - The New Show|website=www.sctvguide.ca|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|1984 || ''[[Love Thy Neighbor (1984 film)|Love Thy Neighbor]]'' || Linda Wilson || Television film<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Show Must Go On: How the Deaths of Lead Actors Have Affected Television Series|last=Snauffer|first=Douglas|publisher=McFarland|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=10}}</ref>\n|-\n|1985 || ''[[Challenge of a Lifetime]]'' || Nora Schoonover || Television film<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/02/14/arts/challenge-of-a-lifetime-with-penny-marshall.html|title='Challenge of a Lifetime,' with Penny Marshall|last=Corry|first=John|date=February 14, 1985|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 20, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|-\n|1990 || ''[[The Simpsons]]'' || Ms. Botz || Voice, Episode: \"[[Some Enchanted Evening (The Simpsons)|Some Enchanted Evening]]\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1993 || ''[[List of The Odd Couple (1970 TV series) episodes#CBS TV-movie: 1993|The Odd Couple: Together Again]]'' || Myrna || Television film<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The Odd Couple on Stage and Screen: A History with Cast and Crew Profiles and an Episode Guide|last=Leszczak|first=Bob|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=83}}</ref>\n|-\n|1996 || ''Saturday Night Live'' || Various Characters || Episode: \"Rosie O'Donnell/Whitney Houston\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|1998 || ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'' || Herself || Episode: \"Hollywood\"\n|-\n|1998 || ''[[Nash Bridges]]'' || Iris Heller || Episode: \"Skin Deep\"\n|-\n|1999 || ''[[Jackie's Back|Jackie's Back!]]'' || Herself || Cameo\n|-\n|2004 || ''[[Frasier]]'' || Celeste || Voice, Episode: \"Frasier-Liste\"\n|-\n|2006 || ''[[Campus Ladies]]'' || || Episode: \"Webcam\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|2006 || ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' || Herself || Episode: \"[[The Woman at the Airport]]\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|2008 || ''[[The Game (U.S. TV series)|The Game]]'' || Doris Fox || Episode: \"A Delectable Basket of Treats\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|2012 || ''[[The Life & Times of Tim]]'' || PR Executive || Voice, Episode: \"The Smug Chiropractor/Corporate Disaster\"\n|-\n|2012 || ''[[Portlandia (TV series)|Portlandia]]'' || Barbara || Episode: \"Feminist Book Store 10th Anniversary\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|2013 || ''[[Sam & Cat]]'' || Sylvia Burke || Episode: \"#SalmonCat\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|2014 || ''[[Mulaney]]'' || Tutti || Episode: \"Sweet Jane\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uticaod.com/article/20140131/NEWS/301319921|title=Penny Marshall and Lorraine Bracco to Play Lesbian Couple on Fox's Mulaney|last=Guide|first=T. V.|website=Uticaod|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016 || ''[[The Odd Couple (2015 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'' || Patty Dombrowski || Episode: \"Taffy Days\", (final appearance)<ref name=\"rs-18dec2018\">{{cite magazine |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=Penny Marshall, Director and 'Laverne & Shirley' Actress, Dead at 75 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/penny-marshall-laverne-shirley-actress-dead-770765/ |access-date=December 18, 2018 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====As director====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|1979 || ''[[Working Stiffs (TV series)|Working Stiffs]]'' || 1 episode: \"The Preview Presentation\"\n|-\n|1979\u20131981 || ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' || 4 episodes: \"Squiggy in Love\", \"The Duke of Squigman\", \"The Dating Game\", \"But Seriously, Folks\"<ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|-\n|1987 || ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]'' || 1 episode\n|-\n|1993 || ''[[A League of Their Own (TV series)|A League of Their Own]]'' || 1 episode: \"Dottie's Back\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/a-league-of-their-own/cast/202631|title=A League of Their Own {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009 || ''[[According to Jim]]'' || 2 episodes: \"The Yoga Bear\", \"Physical Therapy\"<ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|-\n|2010\u20132011 || ''[[United States of Tara]]'' || 2 episodes: \"Explosive Diorama\", \"Wheels\"<ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 1979: [[Golden Globe]] Nominee\u2014Best Performance by an Actress in a Television Series\u2014Musical or Comedy\n* 1978: Golden Globe Nominee\u2014Best Performance by an Actress in a Television Series\u2014Musical or Comedy\n* 1980: Golden Globe Nominee\u2014Best Actress in a Television Series\u2014Comedy or Musical ''Laverne & Shirley<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/penny-marshall/bio/184588/|title=Penny Marshall|website=TV Guide|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref>''<ref>{{cite web |title=Penny Marshall Awards |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001508/awards |website=IMDb |access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* 1988: [[Venice Film Festival]] Winner\u2014Children and Cinema Award\u2014Special Mention for ''Big'' (1988)\n* 1990: [[Saturn Award]] Nominee\u2014Best Director for film ''Big'' (1988) (Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films USA)\n* 1992: [[American Comedy Awards]] Winner\u2014Lifetime Creative Achievement Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/48bf759858b7835d95f86687781881ef|title=Billy Crystal Receives Two Comedy Awards|date=March 29, 1992|website=AP News|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* 1992: [[Hochi Film Awards]] Winner\u2014Best Foreign Film for ''A League of Their Own''\n* 1994: [[New York Women in Film and Television]] Winner of Muse Award\n* 1995: [[Flaiano International Prizes]] Winner\u2014Career Award in Cinema\n* 1997: Elle Women in Hollywood Awards Winner\u2014Icon Award (shared with [[Meryl Streep]], [[Jane Campion]], and [[Laura Ziskin]]){{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* 1998: [[Munich Film Festival]] Winner of High Hopes Award for ''With Friends Like These...''{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* 2000: Online Film & Television Association Winner\u2014OFTA TV Hall of Fame<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oftaawards.com/tv-hall-of-fame/television-hall-of-fame-actors/|title=Television Hall of Fame: Actors|website=Online Film & Television Association|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* 2002: [[Cabourg Romantic Film Festival]]\u2014Golden Swann Winner for film ''Riding in Cars with Boys'' (2001){{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* 2004, Star on the [[Walk of Fame]] at 7021 Hollywood Blvd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walkoffame.com/penny-marshall|title=Penny Marshall|website=Hollywood Walk of Fame|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* 2013: [[Society of Camera Operators]] Winner\u2014Governor's Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/society-of-camera-operators-to-honor-penny-marshall-1118066192/|title=Society of Camera Operators to honor Penny Marshall|last=Fitz-Gerald|first=Sean|last2=Fitz-Gerald|first2=Sean|date=February 14, 2013|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{findagrave|195426118}}\n* {{IMDb name|1508}}\n* {{TCMDb name|id=123130|name=Penny Marshall}}\n* {{Iobdb name|15204}}\n* {{The Interviews name|penny-marshall}}\n* [http://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=11178 Penny Marshall](Aveleyman)..([https://web.archive.org/web/20181105142339/http://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=11178 older version])\n\n{{Penny Marshall}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marshall, Penny}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American film directors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American people of Abruzzese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American stunt performers]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:University of New Mexico alumni]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Women television directors]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n[[Category:Sports spectators]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the British journalist|Penny Marshall (journalist)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| image              = Penny Marshall 1976.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Publicity photo for ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'', 1976\n| birth_name         = Carole Penny Marshall\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1943|10|15|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], U.S.<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|12|17|1943|10|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| resting_place      = [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]], [[Hollywood Hills|Hollywood Hills, California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|director|producer}}\n| years_active       = 1968\u20132018\n| alma_mater         = [[University of New Mexico]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Michael Henry|1963|1966|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Rob Reiner]]|1971|1981|reason=divorced}}\n| relatives          = [[Garry Marshall]] (brother)<br>[[Scott Marshall (director)|Scott Marshall]] (nephew)\n| children           = [[Tracy Reiner]]\n}}\n\n'''Carole Penny Marshall'''<ref name=\"claims\">Born Carole Penny Marshall in 1943, as per ''My Mother Was Nuts, a Memoir'', p. 10; {{ISBN|978-0-547-89262-7}}. Copyright 2012</ref> (October 15, 1943&nbsp;\u2013 December 17, 2018)<ref name=\"claims\" /> was an American actress, director, and producer.  She came to notice in the 1970s for her role as Laverne DeFazio on the television sitcom ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' (1976\u20131983), receiving three nominations for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] for her portrayal.\n\nMarshall made her directorial debut with ''[[Jumpin' Jack Flash (film)|Jumpin' Jack Flash]]'' (1986) before directing ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'' (1988), which became the first film directed by a woman to gross more than $100 million at the U.S. box office. Her subsequent directing credits included ''[[Awakenings]]'' (1990), which was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]], ''[[A League of Their Own]]'' (1992), ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]'' (1994), ''[[The Preacher's Wife]]'' (1996) and ''[[Riding in Cars with Boys]]'' (2001). She also produced ''[[Cinderella Man]]'' (2005) and ''[[Bewitched (2005 film)|Bewitched]]'' (2005), and directed episodes of the TV series ''[[According to Jim]]'' and ''[[United States of Tara]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nCarole Penny Marshall was born in [[the Bronx]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], on October 15, 1943, to Marjorie Irene (n\u00e9e Ward; 1908\u20131983), a tap dance teacher who ran the Marjorie Marshall Dance School, and Anthony \"Tony\" Masciarelli (1906\u20131999), later Anthony Wallace Marshall, a director of [[sponsored film|industrial film]]s and later a producer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comedyontap.com/film/marshall.html |title=Comedy On Tap \u2013 Garry Marshall Interview |publisher=}}</ref> She was the sister of actor/director/TV producer [[Garry Marshall]] and Ronny Hallin, a television producer. Her birth name, Carole, was selected because her mother's favorite actress was [[Carole Lombard]]. Her middle name was selected because her older sister Ronny, wanting a horse in the Bronx, was saving her pennies; her mother chose the middle name in an attempt to console her.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19770624&id=3pc0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=w2gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2534,6209995|work=Kentucky New Era|title=A Penny for your Horsey?|page=10|date=June 24, 1977}}</ref>\n\nHer father was of Italian descent, his family having come from [[Abruzzo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2006/05/26/DDG85J1KVV1.DTL&type=movies|work=The San Francisco Chronicle|first=Mick|last=LaSalle|title=This Jewish boy's life will make you laugh (and get a bit verklempt?)|date=May 26, 2006}}</ref> and her mother was of German, English, and Scottish descent;<ref>[http://www.movieweb.com/news/49/12649.php ''An Interview with the Cast of Keeping up with the Steins''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070418143309/http://www.movieweb.com/news/49/12649.php|date=April 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>[http://www.genealogy.com/famousfolks/pennym/index.html Ancestry of Penny Marshall at Genealogy.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714181811/http://www.genealogy.com/famousfolks/pennym/index.html|date=July 14, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-08-19/sports/0508190168_1_cry-baseball-movies-show-business|title=Penny Marshall|website=Articles.chicagotribune.com}}</ref> Marshall's father changed his last name from Masciarelli to Marshall before she was born.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grouchoreviews.com/index.php?module=subjects&func=viewpage&pageid=157|title=Groucho Reviews: Interview: Garry Marshall\u2014Keeping Up With the Steins\u201405/05/06|author=Peter Canavese|work=GrouchoReviews}}</ref><ref>\"...Anthony \"Tony\" Masciarelli\", a handsome, athletic young man majoring in advertising at New York University ... To better his chances, he changed his last name from Masciarelli to Marshall and forevermore denied that he was both Italian and Catholic\". ''My Mother Was Nuts, a Memoir'', p. 4; {{ISBN|978-0-547-89262-7}}. Copyright  2012.</ref> Religion played no role in the Marshall children's lives. Garry was christened Episcopalian, Ronny was Lutheran, and Penny was confirmed in a [[Congregational church|Congregational Church]], because \"[Mother] sent us anyplace that had a hall where she could put on a recital. If she hadn't needed performance space, we wouldn't have bothered.\"<ref>''My Mother Was Nuts, a Memoir'', p. 18.</ref>\n\nShe grew up at 3235 [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse, the Bronx]], in a building which was also the childhood home of [[Neil Simon]], [[Paddy Chayefsky]], [[Calvin Klein (fashion designer)|Calvin Klein]], and [[Ralph Lauren]].<ref name=Abramowitz>Abramowitz, Rachel (2000). ''Is That a Gun in Your Pocket? Women's Experience of Power in Hollywood''. New York: Random House, {{ISBN|0-679-43754-1}}, p. 289</ref> She began her career as a tap dancer at age three, and later taught tap at her mother's dance school. She graduated from [[Walton High School (New York City)|Walton High School]], a public girls' high school in New York and then went to [[University of New Mexico]] for 2{{frac|1|2}} years where she studied math and psychology. While at UNM, Marshall became pregnant with daughter [[Tracy Reiner]] (n\u00e9e Tracy Henry), and soon after married the father, Michael Henry, in 1963. The couple divorced three years later in 1966. During this period, Marshall worked various jobs to support herself, including working as a [[choreographer]] for the Albuquerque Civic Light Opera Association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Mike |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/penny-marshall-dead-laverne-shirley-star-75-686405 |title=Penny Marshall, 'Laverne & Shirley' Star Turned Director, Dies at 75 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 18, 2018 |access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>  In 1967,<ref name=\"Abramowitz, p. 290\">Abramowitz, p. 290</ref> she moved to Los Angeles to join her older brother Garry, a writer whose credits at the time included TV's ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'' (1961\u20131966).\n\n==Career==\n[[File:1976 Laverne and Shirley.JPG|alt=|thumb|''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'']]\nMarshall first appeared on a television commercial for [[Head & Shoulders|Head and Shoulders]] beautifying shampoo. She was hired to play a girl with stringy, unattractive hair, and [[Farrah Fawcett]] was hired to play a girl with thick, bouncy hair. As the crew was lighting the set, Marshall's stand-in wore a placard that read \"Homely Girl\" and Fawcett's stand-in wore a placard that said \"Pretty Girl\". Fawcett, sensing Marshall's insecurity about her looks, crossed out \"Homely\" on the Marshall stand-in placard and wrote \"Plain\".<ref>Abramowitz, pp. 290\u201391</ref> Marshall and [[Billie Hayes]] were the only actresses to audition for the role of Witchiepoo for ''[[H.R. Pufnstuf]]'', produced by [[Sid and Marty Krofft]]. Marshall thought that she was not right for the part, and Hayes got the role.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 1968 Marshall accepted an offer from her brother to appear in a movie he had written and was producing, called ''How Sweet It Is'' (1968). She landed another small role in the film ''[[The Savage Seven]]'' (1968), as well as a guest appearance on the hit television series ''[[That Girl]]'', starring [[Marlo Thomas]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/dec/19/penny-marshall-obituary|title=Penny Marshall obituary|last=Gilbey|first=Ryan|date=December 19, 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=December 19, 2018|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Marshall was considered for the role of Gloria Bunker Stivic on ''[[All in the Family]],'' but lost the part to [[Sally Struthers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5214817/penny-marshalls-ex-husband-rob-reiner-reacts-to-death-of-former-wife|title=Penny Marshall's Ex-Husband Rob Reiner Reacts To Death Of Former Wife|date=December 18, 2018|website=The Inquisitr|access-date=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, Garry Marshall became the executive producer of the television series ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]''. The following year, Marshall was added to the permanent cast to play a secretary, Myrna, and held the role for four years. In Marshall's final appearance on ''The Odd Couple'', her character married her boyfriend, Sheldn (\"they left the \"o\" off the birth certificate\", she explains), played by Rob Reiner, her real-life husband.<ref name=\":0\"/> The episode included Marshall's real-life siblings, Garry and Ronny, as Myrna's brother and sister.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nWhile she was on ''The Odd Couple'', Marshall played small roles in TV movies such as ''[[Evil Roy Slade]]'' (1972), starring John Astin and [[Mickey Rooney]] (and produced by brother Garry); ''[[The Crooked Hearts]]'' (1972) starring [[Douglas Fairbanks Jr.]], in which she played a waitress; ''The Couple Takes a Wife'', starring [[Bill Bixby]]; and ''Wacky Zoo of Morgan City'' (1972). In 1974, [[James L. Brooks]] and [[Allan Burns]] cast Marshall as Janice Dreyfuss, sister-in-law to Paul Dreyfuss (played by actor [[Paul Sand]]) in the series ''[[Friends and Lovers (TV series)|Paul Sand in Friends and Lovers]]''. It aired on CBS-TV Saturday nights beginning September 14, 1974. Despite good reviews and decent ratings, it was canceled mid-season. Brooks and Burns, along with studio head [[Grant Tinker]], were so impressed with Marshall's comedic talent that the following season, they hired Marshall and actress [[Mary Kay Place]] to play Mary Richards' new neighbors (Paula and Sally Jo) on ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/tv/penny-marshall-memorable-tv-roles/ |title=Penny Marshall's Most Memorable TV Roles, from Laverne & Shirley to Portlandia |website=PEOPLE.com |language=en|access-date=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGarry Marshall, creator and then part-time writer for ''[[Happy Days]]'', cast Marshall and [[Cindy Williams]] to guest on an episode of the show. The installment, titled \"A Date with Fonzie\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0596133 |title=\"Happy Days\" A Date with Fonzie (TV Episode 1975) |work=IMDb}}</ref> aired on November 11, 1975 and introduced the characters Laverne DeFazio and Shirley Feeney (played by Marshall and Williams, respectively). In that episode, Laverne and Shirley were a pair of wisecracking brewery workers who were dates for Fonzie ([[Henry Winkler]]) and Richie ([[Ron Howard]]). The pair were such a hit with the studio audience that Garry Marshall decided to co-create and star them in a successful spinoff, ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' (1976\u20131983).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0074016/ |title=Laverne & Shirley (TV Series 1976\u20131983) |work=IMDb}}</ref> The characters of Laverne and Shirley  appeared in five more episodes of ''Happy Days''. In 1982 at the beginning of ''Laverne & Shirley''{{'}}s eighth season, Williams left the show due to her pregnancy. Marshall continued with the show, but it was canceled after the season's final episode aired in May 1983.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/news/165914_laverne_shirley_star_cindy_williams_spills_show_secrets_new_tell_all |title='Laverne & Shirley' Star Cindy Williams Spills Show Secrets in New Tell-All |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, while still filming ''Laverne & Shirley'', Marshall guest starred on ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]'' in a cameo appearance as herself. In the ''Taxi'' episode \"Louie Moves Uptown,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0718503 |title=\"Taxi\" Louie Moves Uptown (TV Episode 1983) |publisher=IMDb}}</ref> Marshall is turned down for residency in a new high-rise condo in Manhattan. The ''Laverne & Shirley'' episode \"Lost in Spacesuits\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0629057 |title=\"Laverne & Shirley\" Lost in Spacesuits (TV Episode 1982) |work=IMDb}}</ref> is referenced in the scene.\n\nMarshall lent her voice to Ms. Botz, a.k.a. Ms. Botzcowski, the \"babysitter bandit,\" on the [[Some Enchanted Evening (The Simpsons)|first produced episode]] of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', making her the first official guest star to appear on the show, and played a cameo role as herself on the [[HBO]] series ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]''. She also made a cameo appearance alongside her brother Garry in the Disney Halloween-themed movie ''[[Hocus Pocus (1993 film)|Hocus Pocus]]'' as husband and wife. She was reunited with her ''Laverne & Shirley'' co-star, [[Cindy Williams]], on a November 2013 episode of ''[[Sam & Cat]]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |last=Bibel |first=Sara |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/06/26/penny-marshall-and-cindy-williams-to-reunite-on-nickelodeons-sam-cat/189259/ |title=Penny Marshall and Cindy Williams to Reunite on Nickelodeon's 'Sam & Cat' |publisher=TVbytheNumbers |date=June 26, 2013 |access-date=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/laverne-shirley-stars-reunite-nick-comedy-101222356.html |title='Laverne & Shirley' stars reunite on Nick comedy |publisher=Yahoo.com |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tv.yahoo.com/news/laverne-shirley-stars-penny-marshall-cindy-williams-reunite-212429625.html |title=Laverne & Shirley Stars Penny Marshall, Cindy Williams To Reunite on Nickelodeon's Sam & Cat |publisher=Yahoo!TV |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Directing career===\nAt the encouragement of her brother, Marshall became interested in directing.<ref name=\"TribuneBio\">{{cite web |title=Penny Marshall\u2014Director, Producer\u2014Biography |url=https://www.tribute.ca/people/penny-marshall/4854/ |website=Tribute.ca}}</ref> While starring on ''Laverne and Shirley'', she made her debut as a director and directed four episodes of that show<ref>Abramowitz, p. 295</ref> as well as other TV assignments. In 1979, she directed several episodes of the short-lived sitcom ''[[Working Stiffs (TV series)|Working Stiffs]]'', starring [[Michael Keaton]] and [[James Belushi]]. She soon moved on to theatrical films, her first film being ''[[Jumpin' Jack Flash (film)|Jumpin' Jack Flash]]'' (1986) starring [[Whoopi Goldberg]]. She got this gig when the original director dropped out.<ref name=\"TribuneBio\" /> She also gave her daughter Tracy and her brother Garry roles in the film.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nMarshall directed several successful feature films from the mid-1980s onwards, including ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'' (1988) starring [[Tom Hanks]] (the first film directed by a woman to gross over US$100 million), ''[[Awakenings]]'' (1990) starring [[Robin Williams]] and [[Robert De Niro]], ''[[A League of Their Own]]'' (1992) with [[Geena Davis]], [[Tom Hanks]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Rosie O'Donnell]], and ''[[The Preacher's Wife]]'' (1996) starring [[Denzel Washington]] and [[Whitney Houston]]. In 1991, she was awarded the [[Women in Film Los Angeles|Women in Film]] [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards#THE CRYSTAL AWARD|Crystal Award]].<ref name=WIF>{{cite web |title=Past Recipients: Crystal Award |url=http://wif.org/past-recipients |work=Women in Film |access-date=May 10, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630083646/http://www.wif.org/past-recipients |archivedate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010\u20132011, Marshall directed two episodes of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[United States of Tara]]''. In 2013, [[Women in Film and Television International|Women in Film and Video]] presented her with the [[Women in Film & Video-DC Women of Vision Awards|Women of Vision Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wifv.org/programs/women-of-vision-awards/ |title=Women of Vision Awards |work=Women in Film & Video |access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2014, Marshall announced she was developing a biopic on [[Effa Manley]] entitled ''Effa''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yamato |first1=Jen |title=Penny Marshall Back To Baseball With Biopic Of First Female Hall Of Famer |url=http://deadline.com/2014/12/penny-marshall-baseball-movie-effa-manley-league-of-their-own-1201319957 |access-date=December 24, 2014|date=2014-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile at college, Marshall met Michael Henry, a football player, and left to marry him in 1963, aged 20;<ref>{{cite web |title=PENNY MARSHALL'S FAVORITE MISTAKE: GETTING PREGNANT AT 19 |url=http://www.newsweek.com/penny-marshalls-favorite-mistake-getting-pregnant-19-64817 |website=Newsweek|date=2012-09-17 }}</ref> they had one daughter named Tracy in 1964 (now [[Tracy Reiner]]). The marriage lasted three years.<ref name=\"Abramowitz, p. 290\" />\n\nOn April 10, 1971,<ref>California Marriage Index, 1960\u20131985, marriage of Carole P. Marshall and Robert Reiner, Los Angeles</ref> Marshall married actor/director Rob Reiner, who later adopted Tracy. Her marriage to Reiner ended in 1981; the couple had five grandchildren together.<ref>Abramowitz, p. 291</ref>\n\nMarshall had a brief relationship with singer [[Art Garfunkel]] in the mid-1980s, and he credits her with helping him through his depression.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artgarfunkel.com/articles/dailymail2.html |title=Artgarfunkel.com |publisher=Artgarfunkel.com |access-date=November 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMarshall had an abortion after getting pregnant in 1963. In 2010, it was reported that Marshall had been diagnosed with [[lung cancer]] that had metastasized to her brain, but two years later she was 'fine now'.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/10/04/penny-marshall-talks-cancer-abortion-reconciling-with-laverne-shirley-co-star/ |work=Fox |title=Penny Marshall talks cancer, abortion, reconciling with 'Laverne & Shirley co-star in new memoir |author=Gostin, Nicki |date=October 4, 2012 |access-date=September 20, 2015}}</ref> Following her recovery she published a memoir, ''My Mother Was Nuts.''<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death==\nMarshall died in Los Angeles on December 17, 2018, at the age of 75. According to her death certificate, the causes were [[cardiopulmonary]] failure, [[atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease]] and [[diabetes mellitus type 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tmz.vo.llnwd.net/o28/newsdesk/tmz_documents/1231-penny-marshall-death-certificate-tmz.pdf|format=PDF|title=Death Certificate|website=Tmz.vo.llnwd.net|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Dennis McClellan|title=Penny Marshall, who played feisty Laverne in 'Laverne & Shirley' before directing movies, dies at 75 |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-penny-marshall-dies-at-75-story.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=December 18, 2018 |access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/penny-marshalls-cause-of-death-revealed|title=Penny Marshall's cause of death revealed|work=Fox News|date=December 31, 2018|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Marshall's death, her former husband [[Rob Reiner]] took to Twitter to say: \"I loved Penny. I grew up with her. She was born with a great gift. She was born with a funnybone and the instinct of how to use it.  I was very lucky to have lived with her and her funnybone. I will miss her\".<ref>{{cite tweet |author-link=Rob Reiner |user=robreiner |number=1075113203691008000 |date=December 18, 2018 |title=I loved Penny. I grew up with her. She was born with a great gift.|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBroadcaster [[Dan Rather]] tweeted: \"Mourning the loss of a funny, poignant, and original American voice. Penny Marshall was a pioneer in television and the big screen who understood humor comes in many forms and some of life's deeper truths require a laugh. She will be missed.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author-link=Dan Rather |user=danrather |number=1075109150336536576 |date=December 18, 2018 |title=Mourning the loss of a funny, poignant, and original American voice.}}</ref>\n\n[[Ron Howard]], her onetime co-star, and like her an actor who went on to become a celebrated film director, stated on Twitter: \"She was funny & so smart. She made the transition from sitcom star to A List movie director with ease & had a major impact on both media. All that & always relaxed, funny & totally unpretentious. I was lucky to have known & worked with her.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/12/18/us/ap-us-obit-penny-marshall-reactions.html |title=Tom Hanks, Rob Reiner and More Stars Mourn Penny Marshall |last=Press |first=The Associated |date=December 18, 2018 |work=The New York Times|access-date=December 18, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n[[Major League Baseball]] tweeted the following statement: \"We join the baseball community in mourning the passing of Penny Marshall, director of ''A League of Their Own''.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author-link=Major League Baseball |user=mlb |number=1075119175734083585 |date=December 18, 2018 |title=We join the baseball community in mourning the passing of Penny Marshall, director of 'A League of Their Own.|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe day after Marshall's death, ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' co-star [[Cindy Williams]] shared a message on Twitter, simply stating: \"I Love You, Partner.\" Underneath the one line of text was the image of a familiar, cursive 'L' [[initial]]. During the series' run, Marshall had the wardrobe department sew the 'L' on most of her character Laverne's blouses and sweaters.<ref>{{cite tweet |author-link=Cindy Williams |user=Cindy_Williams1 |number= 1075474598068666368 |date=December 19, 2018 |title= I Love You, Partner.}}</ref>\n\nMarshall is interred at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]].  The 'L' from her Laverne character is emblazoned at the bottom of her headstone.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n====As actress====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1968 || ''[[The Savage Seven]]'' || Tina || <ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\">{{cite magazine |last1=Dagan |first1=Carmel |title=Penny Marshall, 'Laverne & Shirley' Star, Director, Dies at 75 |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/penny-marshall-dead-dies-laverne-and-shirley-1203092419/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=December 18, 2018 |date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|1968 || ''[[How Sweet It Is!]]'' || Tour Girl || <ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|-\n|1970 || ''[[The Grasshopper (1970 film)|The Grasshopper]]'' || Plaster Caster || <ref name=\"variety-18dec2018\" />\n|-\n|1970 || ''[[Where's Poppa?]]'' || Courtroom Spectator || Uncredited\n|-\n|1975 || ''How Come Nobody's on Our Side?'' || Theresa || aka ''Capers''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shockcinemamagazine.com/howcome.html|title=How Come Nobody's On Our Side?|website=www.shockcinemamagazine.com|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|1979 || ''[[1941 (film)|1941]]'' || Miss Fitzroy || Uncredited<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/penny-marshall/credits/184588|title=Penny Marshall {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|1985 || ''[[Movers & Shakers]]'' || Reva || Cameo<ref>{{cite book | last=Maltin | first=L. | title=Leonard Maltin's 2015 Movie Guide | publ